data.body:
The current NinePatch implementation is not scalable, making it dependant on the Viewport dimensions.

Code example:

```
package com.test.ninepatch;

import com.badlogic.gdx.ApplicationAdapter;
import com.badlogic.gdx.Gdx;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.Color;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.GL20;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.Texture;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.NinePatch;
import com.badlogic.gdx.scenes.scene2d.utils.NinePatchDrawable;
import com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.SpriteBatch;
import com.badlogic.gdx.scenes.scene2d.Stage;
import com.badlogic.gdx.scenes.scene2d.ui.Button;
import com.badlogic.gdx.scenes.scene2d.ui.Button.ButtonStyle;
import com.badlogic.gdx.utils.viewport.ExtendViewport;

public class NinePatchTest extends ApplicationAdapter {

    private static final float VIEWPORT_HEIGHT = 120f;
    private static final float VIEWPORT_WIDTH = 180f;
//  private static final float VIEWPORT_HEIGHT = 1200f;
//  private static final float VIEWPORT_WIDTH = 1800f;
    Stage stage;
    SpriteBatch batch;
    NinePatchDrawable ninepatchDrawable;
    Button button;

    @Override
    public void create() {
        batch = new SpriteBatch();
        Texture texture = new Texture("ninepatch.png");
        NinePatch ninePatch = new NinePatch(texture, 24, 24, 24, 24);
        // ninePatch.setScale(0.3f, 0.3f);
        NinePatchDrawable ninepatchDrawable = new NinePatchDrawable(
                ninePatch);
        ButtonStyle style = new ButtonStyle(ninepatchDrawable,
                ninepatchDrawable, ninepatchDrawable);
        Button button = new Button(style);
        button.setSize(VIEWPORT_WIDTH / 2f, VIEWPORT_HEIGHT / 2f);
        button.setColor(Color.BLUE);
        button.setPosition(VIEWPORT_WIDTH / 4f, VIEWPORT_HEIGHT / 4f);
        stage = new Stage(new ExtendViewport(VIEWPORT_WIDTH, VIEWPORT_HEIGHT) {
        }, batch);
        stage.addActor(button);

    }

    @Override
    public void render() {
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(1, 0, 0, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
        stage.act();
        stage.draw();
    }

    @Override
    public void resize(int width, int height) {
        stage.getViewport().update(width, height, true);
    }

    @Override
    public void dispose() {
        stage.dispose();
    }
}
```

WARNING! The image ninepathc.png is attached just below but can't be seen because of the white background:
![ninepatch](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1794492/2871918/7cd2727e-d32f-11e3-8211-6df84a15ec22.png)

Execute the test commenting/uncommenting the Viewport constants to see the problem.

![result1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1794492/2871934/8212a55a-d330-11e3-9cc5-dbccb46710b5.png)
![result2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1794492/2871936/8528eb0a-d330-11e3-9333-98cf63f8f193.png)

The second example using a small viewport looks bad, and it could be worse if usin a 10*20 sized Viewport for a game and trying to apply a Ninepatch.

This was reported some time ago here:
https://code.google.com/p/libgdx-users/issues/detail?id=22
https://code.google.com/p/libgdx/issues/detail?id=944

I have the impression it was closed because the issue was not really understood (or because it was Nate's birthday ; )

I'll provide a PR with some modifications to NinePatch to support scaling based on https://gist.github.com/3119086.
